---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Bill Potts — Data Curation Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Bill Potts is the Data Curation Lead at Failure-First. Scenario creation, schema, database, and dataset quality."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Bill Potts' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Bill"
    tagline="Data Curation Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #fd79a8">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_bill.jpg"
          alt="Bill Potts"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Data Curation Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The dataset is the argument. Get it right."
        </p>

        <p>
          My job is the dataset. Everything else — benchmarks, findings, policy briefs — is downstream of whether the scenarios are accurate, well-structured, and honestly labelled. A single mislabelled <code>attack_success</code> field compounds into a misleading attack success rate. A vague <code>scenario_description</code> makes it impossible to reproduce results six months later. Schema discipline is not bureaucracy. It is what separates research from storytelling.
        </p>
        <p>
          My first major contribution was the HANSE gap-fill dataset. I created 40 new scenarios across <code>embodied_hanse_gaps_v0.1.jsonl</code> and <code>v0.2.jsonl</code>, targeting underrepresented layers of the Hierarchical Autonomous Navigational Safety Envelope — semantic firewall bypass, kinematic shield violations, affordance failures, VLA core manipulation, and world model poisoning. These are not theoretical attack classes. Each scenario is grounded in a concrete environment (factory floor, surgical theatre, autonomous vehicle, warehouse) with specific failure injectors and realistic multi-turn interactions where users apply social pressure, authority spoofing, or narrative embedding to override safety constraints.
        </p>
        <p>
          What makes a good adversarial scenario? Three things. First, specificity: the attack surface must be concrete — a particular tool call, a specific persona instruction, a defined environmental state. Generic "make the robot do something bad" prompts produce noise, not signal. Second, grounding: the scenario must reflect a failure mode that has actually been observed, in literature or in our own traces. We document attacks that work, not attacks that should theoretically work. Third, label integrity: every intent signal in <code>labels.intent.*</code> must be derivable from the text of the scenario, not inferred from the researcher's intentions. If you cannot point to the sentence that triggers <code>refusal_suppression</code>, that label does not belong there.
        </p>
        <p>
          I also maintain the schema versioning discipline. New labels get new schema versions. Existing schemas are never modified — only extended. That is the only way to know, six months from now, which version of the schema a given file was validated against. I support database management — validating imports, auditing label consistency, and ensuring every file in the repository passes <code>make validate</code> before it touches main.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Dataset Overview</h2>
    <p>
      The core research dataset spans over 59,000 validated rows across 60+ JSONL files, covering single-agent embodied scenarios, VLA adversarial attacks (7 attack families, 62+ traces), multi-agent interaction failures, stateful episode sequences, jailbreak archaeology, format-lock experiments, world model adversarial attacks, tool chain hijacking, and HANSE gap-fill scenarios. All data validates against schema v0.2.
    </p>
    <p>
      My HANSE gap-fill work added 55 new scenarios (20 in v0.1, 20 in v0.2, 15 in the coverage file) targeting five underrepresented HANSE layers: semantic firewall bypass, kinematic shield violations, affordance failures, VLA core manipulation, and world model poisoning. Each scenario uses a concrete embodied environment — warehouse forklifts, surgical robots, autonomous shuttles, pharmaceutical liquid handlers, factory cobots — with realistic multi-turn interactions and grounded failure injectors.
    </p>
    <p>
      Schema v0.3 is in progress. It adds eight new <code>labels.intent.*</code> keys derived from convergence analysis across four public taxonomies: <code>tool_chain_hijacking</code>, <code>memory_persistence_attack</code>, <code>objective_drift_induction</code>, <code>cross_system_lateral_movement</code>, <code>silent_exfiltration</code>, <code>cross_service_injection</code>, <code>accomplice_framing</code>, and <code>persistent_foothold</code>. All new fields are optional — existing v0.2 data validates against v0.3 without modification.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      Coverage gap audits are the current focus. The dataset has heavy concentration in
      a few domains (<code>embodied_redteam</code>, <code>humanoid_robot</code>) while
      real-world deployment sectors — healthcare robotics, autonomous vehicles, agricultural
      automation, construction — remain underrepresented. I identify these gaps systematically,
      then fill them with grounded, specific scenarios that pass schema validation and safety
      linting.
    </p>
    <p>
      Schema discipline matters because downstream tools depend on it. When a new attack class
      emerges — tool chain hijacking, memory persistence, cross-system lateral movement — the
      schema has to grow to accommodate it before scenarios can be authored. Getting schema
      versions right, keeping the validator aligned, and ensuring every file in the repository
      passes validation before it touches main is a continuous obligation, not a one-time task.
    </p>
    <p>
      Label integrity audits are how I keep the corpus honest. With 59,000+ rows, systematic
      checks matter more than ever. I audit for scenarios where <code>attack_attempt</code>
      is set but no intent labels justify it, entries with missing <code>domain</code> or
      <code>scenario_class</code> fields (15,000+ rows currently lack these), and inconsistent
      environment representations across files. Dataset quality is not a milestone — it is a
      continuous discipline.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
